<subsection xml:id="subsec-conversion-of-actual-length-to-scale-length">
    <title>Conversion of actual length to scale length</title>
    <p>
        To convert an actual length to a scale length, divide the actual length by the scale factor, which represents how much real-world distance corresponds to one unit of measurement on the drawing or map.
    </p>
    <p>
        Actual length is the real-world length of the same object. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Scale length refers to the length of an object as represented in the drawing or model.
    </p>
    <p>
        To convert an actual length to a scale length, you divide the actual length by the scale factor, which is typically expressed as a ratio (e.g., <m>1:100</m>).
    </p>
    <p>
        For example, a scale like 1:100 means that 1 unit on the drawing represents 100 units in real life.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key points on conversion of actual to scale length.}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Identify the scale: Determine the ratio of the drawing to the real-life object (e.g., <m>1:25, 1:100, 1:500</m>).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Divide the real length: Take the actual length and divide it by the scale factor.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Scale Length = <m>\frac{\textbf{Actual length}}{\textbf{Scale Factor}}</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
