    <p>
        Learning point
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    To covert actual length to scale length, the actual length is divided by a given factor scale.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The length of a building is <m>15 \textbf{m}</m>. John drew the building using a scale where <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>3 \textbf{m} </m>. Determine the length of the drawing.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Length of the actual building = <m>15 \textbf{m}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Scale = <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>3 \textbf{m} </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>15 \textbf{m}</m> is represented by:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp \frac{15 \cancel{m}}{1 \cancel{m}} \times 1 \textbf{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 5 \textbf{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, The length of the drawing is <m>5 \textbf{cm}</m>
            </p>

        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Calculate the scale length that corresponds to an actual bridge length of 120 meters for the given scales;
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>20 \textbf{m} </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>1 \textbf{km} </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>80 \textbf{m} </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>100 \textbf{m} </m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Actual length of the bridge = <m>120 \textbf{m}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>20 \textbf{m} </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \amp \frac{120 \cancel{m}}{20 \cancel{m}} \times 1 \textbf{cm}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 6 \textbf{cm}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The scale length is, <m>6 \textbf{cm}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>1 \textbf{km} </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            First, we need to convert <m> \textbf{km}</m> to <m> \textbf{m}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Since, <m>1 \textbf{km}</m> = <m>1000 \textbf{m} </m>, we convert:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \amp \frac{1 \cancel{km}}{1 \cancel{km}} \times 1000 \textbf{m}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 1000 \textbf{m}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>1000 \textbf{m} </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \amp \frac{120 \textbf{m}}{1000 \textbf{m}} = 0.12\textbf{cm}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The scale length is , <m>0.12 \textbf{cm}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>80 \textbf{m} </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \amp \frac{120 \cancel{m}}{80 \cancel{m}} \times 1 \textbf{cm}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 1.5 \textbf{cm}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The scale length is, <m>1.5 \textbf{cm}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>100 \textbf{m} </m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \amp \frac{120 \cancel{m}}{100 \cancel{m}} \times 1 \textbf{cm}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 1.2 \textbf{cm}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The scale length is, <m>1.2 \textbf{cm}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A map is drawn to a scale of <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>5 \textbf{km} </m>. Two towns A and B are <m>200 \textbf{km}</m> apart. What is the distance between the two towns on the map.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Actual distance between towns A and B: <m>200 \textbf{km}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Scale: <m>1 \textbf{cm}</m> represents <m>5 \textbf{km} </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Map distance}</m> = <m>\textbf{Actual ditance} \div \textbf{Scale factor}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp \frac{200 \cancel{km}}{5 \cancel{km}} \times 1 \textbf{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 40 \textbf{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, Therefore, the distance between towns A and B on the map is <m>40 \textbf{cm}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
